{
  "texts": [
    "Representations of this type are graph-based representations, which model atoms or residues as nodes of a graph, while edges between nodes recapitulate closeness in space and chemical bonds.",
    "As such, they are also well-suited to build ML models that can capture local symmetries and generate predictions that are invariant under geometrical transformations like rotations 51.",
    "The choice of a representation depends on reasons of data availability, computational expediency, and is informed by domain knowledge, which can suggest the data characteristics ('features') or the level of approximation most adequate to a given prediction task.",
    "The main idea behind feature-based ML is to select and design sets of features to use as data representations that are fed into a ML method as inputs.",
    "Features to describe protein regions of interest typically summarize their biochemical (for example, hydrophobicity, polarity) and geometrical (for example, surface area, accessibility) properties."
  ]
}